def bucket_key(shock):
    return f"{classify_league(shock.slug)}|" \
           f"{classify_favoritism(shock.pre_price)}|" \
           f"{classify_depth(shock.bids)}|" \
           f"{classify_time(shock.elapsed_ms)}|" \
           f"{classify_goal(shock.goal_diff)}"

# Example output:
# "deep|underdog|balanced|mid|level"
That key, deep underdog balanced mid level, is a complete description of the state of the world at the instant of the shock. It reads as a major league, underdog team, balanced order book, mid match, tied score. There are 720 possible combinations. In practice around 200 have enough data to trade. This key is how the strategy looks up exactly how deep this specific type of shock has historically gone.
Part 3: Getting the Data and Building Historical Distributions

This is where the strategy becomes genuinely quantitative. But before you can build a single distribution, you need historical football match data from Polymarket. This is the part most people get stuck on, so let me save you the time.
